1
00:00:10,800 --> 00:00:11,833
<i> Uncle Noah?</i>

2
00:00:15,267 --> 00:00:16,133
<i> Thank you.</i>

3
00:00:17,767 --> 00:00:19,967
<i>Sweetheart,
maybe that will help you.</i>

4
00:00:20,100 --> 00:00:21,533
<i> Thank you for coming.</i>

5
00:00:21,667 --> 00:00:23,900
<i> We're all here for you.</i>

6
00:00:24,033 --> 00:00:25,800
<i> We won't leave you, dear.</i>

7
00:00:25,933 --> 00:00:27,133
<i> Where's the accused?</i>

8
00:00:27,267 --> 00:00:31,567
<i>Do you understand the charges
against you, Miss Cruz?</i>

9
00:00:32,900 --> 00:00:34,067
<i> Yes, Your Honor.</i>

10
00:00:34,233 --> 00:00:36,633
<i> And how do you plead?</i>

11
00:00:36,767 --> 00:00:38,000
<i> Not guilty, Your Honor.</i>

12
00:00:38,133 --> 00:00:40,633
<i> You animal! You liar!</i>

13
00:00:40,767 --> 00:00:43,100
<i>- "Not guilty," really?
- Mrs. Cruz!</i>

14
00:00:43,233 --> 00:00:46,133
<i>You killed my daughter!
You killed her!</i>

15
00:00:46,267 --> 00:00:47,200
<i> What are you...</i>

16
00:00:47,333 --> 00:00:49,900
<i>It feels different inside,
doesn't it, Mom?</i>

17
00:00:50,033 --> 00:00:51,633
<i> You did well, Coleen.</i>

18
00:00:51,767 --> 00:00:53,200
<i> Just stick to the truth.</i>

19
00:00:53,333 --> 00:00:55,367
<i>That's what
will keep you strong.</i>

20
00:00:55,500 --> 00:00:56,800
<i> Thank you, Attorney.</i>

21
00:00:56,933 --> 00:00:58,133
<i> Where's Noah, by the way?</i>

22
00:00:58,267 --> 00:01:00,700
<i>Thank you for accepting
my invitation.</i>

23
00:01:00,833 --> 00:01:02,567
<i> Tell me what I need to know.</i>

24
00:01:02,700 --> 00:01:04,733
<i> I want us to team up.</i>

25
00:01:04,867 --> 00:01:06,667
<i> So you can get Felma,</i>

26
00:01:06,800 --> 00:01:08,867
<i> and I can get my husband back.</i>

27
00:01:12,967 --> 00:01:14,167
<i> Here, sweetie.</i>

28
00:01:14,300 --> 00:01:18,167
Let's just play so you're not
stuck in your room.

29
00:01:25,500 --> 00:01:26,433
Are you okay?

30
00:01:28,433 --> 00:01:30,133
Yes.

31
00:01:32,800 --> 00:01:35,767
I was just thinking
about Jessica.

32
00:01:35,900 --> 00:01:38,900
It would've been nice
if you were all together...

33
00:01:39,033 --> 00:01:40,300
getting along.

34
00:01:43,700 --> 00:01:44,833
Is that all
you're thinking about,

35
00:01:44,967 --> 00:01:45,900
or is there something else?

36
00:01:49,200 --> 00:01:51,500
Who else would I think about?

37
00:01:51,633 --> 00:01:52,967
Uncle Noah.

38
00:01:56,067 --> 00:01:57,500
So?

39
00:01:57,633 --> 00:01:59,667
What do you say?

40
00:01:59,800 --> 00:02:03,300
Let's work together
so you can get Felma back.

41
00:02:04,667 --> 00:02:06,500
Why do you think
I'd agree this time?

42
00:02:08,200 --> 00:02:10,667
Noah, you need my help.

43
00:02:10,800 --> 00:02:13,833
Back then, even when Felma
and Manuel weren't okay,

44
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:14,967
you still couldn't win her back.

45
00:02:15,100 --> 00:02:16,833
How much more now...

46
00:02:16,967 --> 00:02:18,267
that they've reconciled?

47
00:02:18,400 --> 00:02:20,100
Their family is whole again.

48
00:02:21,133 --> 00:02:24,967
It's hard to break a family
when you're acting alone.

49
00:02:30,700 --> 00:02:34,167
I'm not doing anything
to break their family.

50
00:02:35,567 --> 00:02:37,700
I'm just helping Coleen.

51
00:02:39,033 --> 00:02:42,367
Oh, come on. Seriously?
I'm not stupid.

52
00:02:42,500 --> 00:02:45,533
You wouldn't come back into
Felma's life for Coleen.

53
00:02:46,900 --> 00:02:47,733
It's true.

54
00:02:49,367 --> 00:02:52,733
The truth is,
you saw an opportunity.

55
00:02:52,867 --> 00:02:54,500
You're helping Coleen

56
00:02:54,633 --> 00:02:58,033
because you want to look like
a hero to Felma.

57
00:02:58,167 --> 00:03:01,400
You want her to regret
rejecting you before.

58
00:03:01,533 --> 00:03:03,633
And realize that...

59
00:03:03,767 --> 00:03:06,700
you're the one
she should've loved, not Manuel.

60
00:03:08,267 --> 00:03:09,300
You know,

61
00:03:10,700 --> 00:03:13,233
I accepted a long time ago
that Felma will never love me.

62
00:03:14,933 --> 00:03:16,700
You're the one
who can't accept

63
00:03:16,833 --> 00:03:18,500
that Manuel
doesn't love you anymore.

64
00:03:19,867 --> 00:03:20,867
Now...

65
00:03:22,300 --> 00:03:24,567
to answer your question,

66
00:03:24,700 --> 00:03:27,333
I'm not teaming up with you

67
00:03:27,467 --> 00:03:29,167
just to get Felma back.

68
00:03:30,567 --> 00:03:33,667
I don't have any intention
of doing that.

69
00:03:38,467 --> 00:03:40,233
Why would I even
think about Noah?

70
00:03:43,033 --> 00:03:44,300
Dad,

71
00:03:45,633 --> 00:03:47,500
we're not kids anymore.

72
00:03:48,667 --> 00:03:52,700
Of course, we notice
when things get awkward.

73
00:03:57,267 --> 00:03:59,067
Maybe...

74
00:03:59,200 --> 00:04:02,067
I'm just not used
to having him around again.

75
00:04:02,200 --> 00:04:04,867
Unlike you, guys.
You act like nothing's changed.

76
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:07,167
Even after being apart
for so long,

77
00:04:07,300 --> 00:04:10,100
it's like everything's the same.
You're still friends.

78
00:04:10,233 --> 00:04:13,167
Uncle Noah isn't
just a friend to us, Dad.

79
00:04:13,300 --> 00:04:15,433
He's like a father to us, too.

80
00:04:17,600 --> 00:04:19,733
But, Dad,

81
00:04:19,867 --> 00:04:22,233
please don't take what I said
the wrong way.

82
00:04:22,367 --> 00:04:25,233
You're still our dad.

83
00:04:25,367 --> 00:04:28,367
And from the very start,
I've been Team Manuel.

84
00:04:28,533 --> 00:04:31,600
Those two were Team Noah.

85
00:04:31,733 --> 00:04:32,700
Hey!

86
00:04:32,833 --> 00:04:34,033
We're not denying it.

87
00:04:34,167 --> 00:04:38,200
And dad knows that Uncle Noah
helped us when he wasn't here.

88
00:04:39,567 --> 00:04:41,567
And...

89
00:04:41,700 --> 00:04:45,933
yeah, we did try
to push him toward mom.

90
00:04:46,067 --> 00:04:48,500
But they were never meant to be.

91
00:04:48,633 --> 00:04:50,667
Because you and mom are
the ones meant for each other.

92
00:04:50,800 --> 00:04:51,667
Yes!

93
00:04:51,800 --> 00:04:52,667
That's it.

94
00:04:52,800 --> 00:04:54,567
So we, your kids...

95
00:04:54,700 --> 00:04:56,900
Of course,
you're our only dad.

96
00:04:57,033 --> 00:04:59,300
- You're the one and only.
- Let me join!

97
00:04:59,433 --> 00:05:00,967
- Come here.
- I want that spot!

98
00:05:01,133 --> 00:05:04,400
Yes, yes, that's it.

99
00:05:04,533 --> 00:05:07,300
Thank you so much, kids.

100
00:05:07,433 --> 00:05:08,933
You know,

101
00:05:09,067 --> 00:05:13,200
it means a lot that you accepted
me again as your father.

102
00:05:14,600 --> 00:05:17,000
Let's hug dad even tighter!

103
00:05:21,300 --> 00:05:22,267
Noah.

104
00:05:24,067 --> 00:05:25,367
Noah, wait.

105
00:05:25,500 --> 00:05:27,267
You have to understand.

106
00:05:30,467 --> 00:05:33,333
What else is there
to understand?

107
00:05:33,467 --> 00:05:35,033
You.

108
00:05:35,200 --> 00:05:36,867
What you feel.

109
00:05:37,900 --> 00:05:39,833
I can see right
through you.

110
00:05:39,967 --> 00:05:41,233
You still love Felma.

111
00:05:41,367 --> 00:05:43,500
Yes.

112
00:05:43,633 --> 00:05:45,300
And so what?

113
00:05:45,433 --> 00:05:46,667
Hazel,

114
00:05:46,800 --> 00:05:49,333
I'm still not
going to do anything...

115
00:05:49,467 --> 00:05:51,500
to win her back.

116
00:05:51,633 --> 00:05:54,067
Because someone
who truly loves...

117
00:05:54,200 --> 00:05:56,000
knows how to let go.

118
00:05:57,800 --> 00:05:59,767
Unlike you.

119
00:05:59,900 --> 00:06:01,867
What you have...

120
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:04,000
that's obsession.

121
00:06:04,133 --> 00:06:06,267
You're obsessing
over Manuel.

122
00:06:07,667 --> 00:06:09,100
Obsessed? Fine, I'm obsessed.

123
00:06:10,500 --> 00:06:14,700
But at least I'm not
denying what I feel.

124
00:06:14,833 --> 00:06:16,133
Unlike you.

125
00:06:17,900 --> 00:06:20,833
Hazel, you think I don't
see what you're doing?

126
00:06:20,967 --> 00:06:23,067
You're using me...

127
00:06:23,200 --> 00:06:24,900
to get your husband back.

128
00:06:26,667 --> 00:06:28,700
Well...

129
00:06:28,833 --> 00:06:30,133
tough luck.

130
00:06:32,300 --> 00:06:34,967
Because I'm not doing that.

131
00:06:35,100 --> 00:06:37,533
I love Felma's family,

132
00:06:37,667 --> 00:06:40,300
and I will never let anyone
destroy it.

133
00:06:54,233 --> 00:06:56,167
That's Sisig, right, Jeff?

134
00:06:56,300 --> 00:06:57,200
Yes.

135
00:06:57,600 --> 00:06:59,267
Longganisa.

136
00:07:06,333 --> 00:07:07,600
- Oh, hello, guard. Hi.
- Sir, good morning.

137
00:07:07,733 --> 00:07:09,233
- Long time no see.
- Sir Noah!

138
00:07:09,367 --> 00:07:11,267
There he is!

139
00:07:11,400 --> 00:07:12,200
- Uncle!
- You all look surprised.

140
00:07:12,333 --> 00:07:13,367
Good morning, everyone.

141
00:07:13,500 --> 00:07:15,033
- Hello!
- We missed you, Sir!

142
00:07:16,567 --> 00:07:17,933
How are you?

143
00:07:18,067 --> 00:07:20,300
Friend, where are the documents
you wanted to show me?

144
00:07:21,833 --> 00:07:23,567
<i> Sir, we missed you!</i>

145
00:07:25,400 --> 00:07:26,633
Feels like everyone's surprised.

146
00:07:26,767 --> 00:07:28,333
- They just missed you, Uncle.
- Yes.

147
00:07:30,133 --> 00:07:31,300
That's Noah's voice.

148
00:07:37,333 --> 00:07:38,800
Noah!

149
00:07:38,933 --> 00:07:40,167
- Hey!
- You're here!

150
00:07:40,533 --> 00:07:41,567
Felma.

151
00:07:41,867 --> 00:07:43,033
Yes.

152
00:07:43,167 --> 00:07:45,467
You didn't say you were coming.
We could've prepared something.

153
00:07:45,600 --> 00:07:47,267
Oh, come on, don't treat me
like a visitor.

154
00:07:47,400 --> 00:07:48,633
You guys.

155
00:07:48,800 --> 00:07:52,200
No, really. It could've been
a proper homecoming.

156
00:07:53,500 --> 00:07:56,033
Is that so?
Well, it's not too late.

157
00:07:56,167 --> 00:07:59,633
Let's just order in.

158
00:07:59,767 --> 00:08:01,833
Anything you want, guys.

159
00:08:01,967 --> 00:08:03,400
- Let's do takeout.
- Yes!

160
00:08:03,533 --> 00:08:04,567
I'll order.

161
00:08:04,700 --> 00:08:05,867
- Andrea is good at this.
- I'll handle the drinks.

162
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:06,800
I got the drinks.

163
00:08:06,933 --> 00:08:08,033
- Paper cups.
- Hurry.

164
00:08:08,167 --> 00:08:10,767
- Pizza! Pizza!
- I'll handle it, Mom.

165
00:08:17,800 --> 00:08:18,933
Sir Manuel?

166
00:08:19,067 --> 00:08:20,100
Hey.

167
00:08:20,233 --> 00:08:23,800
Here's everything you asked me
to buy, Sir. There.

168
00:08:23,967 --> 00:08:25,767
- You know...
- Thanks.

169
00:08:25,900 --> 00:08:27,967
What exactly are you doing
with all that?

170
00:08:28,100 --> 00:08:30,367
There, look.

171
00:08:30,500 --> 00:08:33,000
I'm making a scrapbook.

172
00:08:33,133 --> 00:08:34,900
I'll surprise Coleen.

173
00:08:35,900 --> 00:08:38,567
Looks like Sir Manuel's
in a good mood.

174
00:08:40,433 --> 00:08:42,700
Let's just say..

175
00:08:42,833 --> 00:08:45,300
my family really loves me,

176
00:08:45,433 --> 00:08:47,667
and I have no reason
to get jealous anymore.

177
00:08:51,500 --> 00:08:54,467
You, Didang. You're so nosy.

178
00:08:54,633 --> 00:08:57,133
What? I'm not nosy, Sir.

179
00:08:57,267 --> 00:08:59,000
I'm just observant.

180
00:09:01,100 --> 00:09:02,400
You, really.

181
00:09:03,233 --> 00:09:04,367
No, it's okay.

182
00:09:09,967 --> 00:09:12,567
We've become stricter with...

183
00:09:12,700 --> 00:09:15,367
production facilities
and quality control.

184
00:09:15,500 --> 00:09:18,633
Especially after
the business got sabotaged.

185
00:09:19,667 --> 00:09:21,867
Maybe it was a blessing
in disguise.

186
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:25,833
Our overall sales
went up by 20%.

187
00:09:28,833 --> 00:09:30,100
That's great to hear.

188
00:09:33,100 --> 00:09:35,133
It really hits differently
when...

189
00:09:35,267 --> 00:09:37,600
you hear it directly,

190
00:09:37,733 --> 00:09:41,200
not just reading about it
in reports.

191
00:09:44,267 --> 00:09:45,433
<i> Mom, eat now.</i>

192
00:09:45,567 --> 00:09:46,533
Here you go.

193
00:09:46,667 --> 00:09:48,100
Thanks, dear.

194
00:09:50,967 --> 00:09:53,967
Noah, thank you
for everything you taught me.

195
00:09:54,100 --> 00:09:56,167
I wouldn't be able to manage
this business

196
00:09:56,300 --> 00:09:58,400
if you hadn't guided me
back then.

197
00:10:00,200 --> 00:10:02,000
Come on, Felma.

198
00:10:02,167 --> 00:10:03,800
You still haven't changed.

199
00:10:03,933 --> 00:10:05,233
You're still so humble.

200
00:10:06,933 --> 00:10:08,633
Not everything came from me.

201
00:10:09,967 --> 00:10:12,467
You have your own efficient way
of doing things, too.

202
00:10:16,333 --> 00:10:19,833
- Thank you, son.
- There, enjoy.

203
00:10:19,967 --> 00:10:22,100
- Cheers?
- Cheers.

204
00:10:22,233 --> 00:10:23,567
Cheers.

205
00:10:31,033 --> 00:10:31,933
Dad...

206
00:10:33,200 --> 00:10:36,533
thank you for everything
you and mom are doing for me,

207
00:10:36,700 --> 00:10:38,800
so I won't be tense
for the hearing.

208
00:10:42,100 --> 00:10:43,967
Yes, dear, but...

209
00:10:44,633 --> 00:10:47,100
is this really helping?

210
00:10:47,233 --> 00:10:50,800
Doesn't it just bring
everything back?

211
00:10:50,933 --> 00:10:54,400
I want Jessica
to remember us like this.

212
00:10:55,767 --> 00:10:57,100
Happy.

213
00:10:59,267 --> 00:11:00,333
Us.

214
00:11:02,333 --> 00:11:03,533
Dad,

215
00:11:03,667 --> 00:11:07,400
do you think
she already forgave me?

216
00:11:07,533 --> 00:11:10,467
Dear, how would you
describe Jessica?

217
00:11:13,500 --> 00:11:14,567
She's kind.

218
00:11:16,633 --> 00:11:17,900
She gives good advice.

219
00:11:19,667 --> 00:11:21,967
And she's really patient.

220
00:11:23,200 --> 00:11:24,933
Even when I fought with her,

221
00:11:26,667 --> 00:11:28,367
she still tried
to understand me.

222
00:11:29,500 --> 00:11:30,667
See?

223
00:11:30,800 --> 00:11:31,967
There.

224
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:34,733
You already answered
your own question.

225
00:11:36,833 --> 00:11:39,433
I raised Jessica.

226
00:11:39,567 --> 00:11:42,100
I know her very well.

227
00:11:42,267 --> 00:11:46,567
Yes, you fought,
you hurt each other...

228
00:11:46,867 --> 00:11:48,567
but...

229
00:11:48,700 --> 00:11:52,233
she always wished
you two would make up.

230
00:11:53,600 --> 00:11:55,667
So, dear, I'm sure

231
00:11:55,800 --> 00:11:57,567
she already forgave you.

232
00:11:58,933 --> 00:12:02,000
And that's why you should
forgive yourself, too, okay?

233
00:12:03,567 --> 00:12:07,467
Because if you let the guilt
stay, it will only weaken you.

234
00:12:08,833 --> 00:12:11,300
You'll have a harder time
facing the hearing.

235
00:12:13,533 --> 00:12:15,100
Listen.

236
00:12:15,667 --> 00:12:18,333
Just focus on...

237
00:12:18,467 --> 00:12:20,033
telling the truth.

238
00:12:21,433 --> 00:12:23,500
That you did nothing wrong.

239
00:12:23,900 --> 00:12:26,500
And when you do that,

240
00:12:26,633 --> 00:12:29,567
you're giving justice
to Jessica's death.

241
00:12:31,600 --> 00:12:32,100
Okay?

242
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:38,300
Thank you.

243
00:12:39,600 --> 00:12:43,833
Thank you for never getting
tired of encouraging me.

244
00:12:58,567 --> 00:13:01,300
It's not like
I'm efficient all the time.

245
00:13:02,300 --> 00:13:03,933
When it comes
to being a mother...

246
00:13:04,967 --> 00:13:06,233
no matter what I do...

247
00:13:07,767 --> 00:13:09,833
I can't lift Coleen's spirits.

248
00:13:10,867 --> 00:13:11,967
It feels like...

249
00:13:13,233 --> 00:13:14,233
it's still not enough.

250
00:13:15,267 --> 00:13:16,267
Felma...

251
00:13:17,767 --> 00:13:21,167
you don't have to fill
every gap.

252
00:13:22,633 --> 00:13:24,667
Andrea and Jeffrey are there.

253
00:13:24,800 --> 00:13:26,000
Manuel is there.

254
00:13:27,633 --> 00:13:28,767
And I'm here...

255
00:13:30,100 --> 00:13:31,267
to support all of you.

256
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:35,533
I can help Coleen, too.

257
00:13:40,400 --> 00:13:41,867
Thank you, Noah.

258
00:13:43,233 --> 00:13:45,400
You still haven't changed.

259
00:13:45,533 --> 00:13:47,100
You're still a good friend.

260
00:13:51,967 --> 00:13:53,200
So...

261
00:13:53,333 --> 00:13:54,600
shall we eat?

262
00:13:58,033 --> 00:14:00,533
<i>Counsel, you may call your first
witness.</i>

263
00:14:01,867 --> 00:14:07,500
Your Honor, may I call on
Mr. Timothy Malabanan

264
00:14:07,633 --> 00:14:08,900
to the stand?

265
00:14:20,100 --> 00:14:26,267
Mr. Malabanan, can you state
again what your job is?

266
00:14:26,400 --> 00:14:28,400
I'm a driver.

267
00:14:28,567 --> 00:14:31,700
I work as Miss Lani
Benitez's driver.

268
00:14:32,067 --> 00:14:33,667
<i> Do you remember where you were</i>

269
00:14:33,800 --> 00:14:36,600
on November 3, 2025,

270
00:14:36,933 --> 00:14:39,400
at around two
in the afternoon?

271
00:14:39,533 --> 00:14:43,833
Yes, Sir, I was driving in front
of Southcrest Hospital.

272
00:14:44,200 --> 00:14:46,967
Around two in the afternoon,
I think.

273
00:14:47,100 --> 00:14:51,833
Can you tell us what happened...

274
00:14:51,967 --> 00:14:54,967
as you were passing
through that area?

275
00:14:55,100 --> 00:14:57,333
I saw on the sidewalk...

276
00:14:57,467 --> 00:14:59,167
two women fighting.

277
00:14:59,300 --> 00:15:01,100
One of them was Coleen Cruz.

278
00:15:02,167 --> 00:15:04,300
<i> She pushed the victim.</i>

279
00:15:05,600 --> 00:15:07,600
<i> It all happened fast.</i>

280
00:15:07,733 --> 00:15:08,733
<i> I tried to hit the brakes,</i>

281
00:15:08,867 --> 00:15:12,267
but I had already hit the woman.

282
00:15:12,400 --> 00:15:13,567
That's not true!

283
00:15:14,233 --> 00:15:15,067
He's lying!

284
00:15:15,200 --> 00:15:16,500
- I didn't push my sister!
- Counsel!

285
00:15:16,633 --> 00:15:18,667
<i> Counsel, restrain your client.</i>

286
00:15:18,800 --> 00:15:19,967
<i> Apologies, Your Honor.</i>

287
00:15:20,100 --> 00:15:21,967
Coleen, please.

288
00:15:22,100 --> 00:15:23,933
You'll have your time
to testify.

289
00:15:24,067 --> 00:15:25,900
Right now, let me do my job.

290
00:15:26,033 --> 00:15:27,633
That would be all, Your Honor.

291
00:15:27,767 --> 00:15:29,800
- Cross?
- Yes, Sir.

292
00:15:31,700 --> 00:15:32,967
Mr. Malabanan...

293
00:15:35,700 --> 00:15:39,267
you said earlier that everything
happened quickly.

294
00:15:41,333 --> 00:15:45,167
<i>How far were you
from the two women you saw...</i>

295
00:15:45,300 --> 00:15:47,233
<i> before you hit the victim?</i>

296
00:15:49,233 --> 00:15:55,300
Maybe around 40 to 50 meters
from where I was.

297
00:15:56,667 --> 00:15:57,767
How fast were you going?

298
00:15:58,800 --> 00:16:01,967
Just normal speed, maybe around
60 kilometers per hour.

299
00:16:04,633 --> 00:16:06,033
And while you were driving...

300
00:16:07,500 --> 00:16:09,467
you were focused
on the road, correct?

301
00:16:10,567 --> 00:16:11,433
<i> Yes, Sir.</i>

302
00:16:11,567 --> 00:16:13,567
I could see them clearly.

303
00:16:17,167 --> 00:16:21,000
You also said earlier that
you saw two women...

304
00:16:21,500 --> 00:16:23,200
who seemed to be arguing.

305
00:16:23,333 --> 00:16:24,700
<i>- Yes.
- And you heard</i>

306
00:16:24,833 --> 00:16:26,633
what they were talking about,
didn't you?

307
00:16:28,167 --> 00:16:30,500
- No, Sir.
- You didn't?

308
00:16:30,633 --> 00:16:32,800
<i>Well, since you didn't hear
what they were saying.</i>

309
00:16:33,667 --> 00:16:37,300
So, you're also not sure
they were really fighting.

310
00:16:37,433 --> 00:16:38,400
Correct?

311
00:16:41,733 --> 00:16:42,933
Correct.

312
00:16:43,067 --> 00:16:44,067
There.

313
00:16:46,733 --> 00:16:50,533
So is it possible that you're
only saying the accused pushed

314
00:16:50,667 --> 00:16:53,067
the victim
so someone else would be blamed

315
00:16:53,200 --> 00:16:54,600
for hitting her?

316
00:16:56,733 --> 00:16:58,867
That's not what happened, Sir.

317
00:17:00,300 --> 00:17:02,100
I was charged, too.

318
00:17:03,400 --> 00:17:04,500
But I really saw it.

319
00:17:04,633 --> 00:17:08,433
It was clear as day that
that woman pushed the victim.

320
00:17:08,567 --> 00:17:09,700
She pushed her!

321
00:17:09,833 --> 00:17:11,500
It was even like this!

322
00:17:25,167 --> 00:17:27,967
<i>Counsel, you may now call
your next witness.</i>

323
00:17:28,933 --> 00:17:30,300
Mrs. Cruz,

324
00:17:32,400 --> 00:17:36,300
how are you related
to the accused?

325
00:17:37,300 --> 00:17:38,667
Miss Coleen Cruz?

326
00:17:42,433 --> 00:17:43,567
She's the daughter of...

327
00:17:46,500 --> 00:17:47,867
my husband's mistress.

328
00:17:53,267 --> 00:17:55,267
Where were you...

329
00:17:55,400 --> 00:17:59,433
on the day Jessica was hit
by the car, Mrs. Cruz?

330
00:18:00,467 --> 00:18:03,900
I was at Southcrest
Premier Hospital.

331
00:18:05,033 --> 00:18:06,400
And what were you doing there?

332
00:18:10,833 --> 00:18:11,800
I wanted to...

333
00:18:13,533 --> 00:18:17,067
take my husband back
from his mistress.

334
00:18:20,367 --> 00:18:26,800
But then I saw Coleen
hurting Jessica.

335
00:18:27,800 --> 00:18:29,500
<i>- Jessica, please! Jessica!
- No!</i>

336
00:18:29,633 --> 00:18:32,100
<i>- Hey!
- You want me to die...</i>

337
00:18:32,233 --> 00:18:34,133
When you saw, Mrs. Cruz,

338
00:18:34,267 --> 00:18:37,200
that Coleen hurting Jessica...

339
00:18:37,333 --> 00:18:38,267
what did you do?

340
00:18:40,067 --> 00:18:41,600
I helped my daughter.

341
00:18:43,233 --> 00:18:45,167
Then I scolded Coleen.

342
00:18:46,167 --> 00:18:49,567
But suddenly,
her siblings arrived.

343
00:18:50,167 --> 00:18:51,733
And they had people with them.

344
00:18:52,467 --> 00:18:53,700
There were so many of them.

345
00:18:55,300 --> 00:18:56,700
They ganged up on me.

346
00:18:56,833 --> 00:18:58,167
<i>- Wait!
-I haven't taken my revenge yet!</i>

347
00:18:58,300 --> 00:19:00,133
<i>- Wait! That's my friend!
- Stop it!</i>

348
00:19:00,267 --> 00:19:01,267
Liar!

349
00:19:02,200 --> 00:19:03,267
We were just defending Coleen!

350
00:19:03,400 --> 00:19:04,267
You were hurting her!

351
00:19:04,800 --> 00:19:06,100
Order!

352
00:19:08,333 --> 00:19:10,700
Mrs. Cruz, you may proceed.

353
00:19:12,033 --> 00:19:13,633
I was surprised to see...

354
00:19:14,733 --> 00:19:16,933
that Jessica
and Coleen were gone.

355
00:19:17,900 --> 00:19:24,200
So I followed them
toward the road.

356
00:19:25,933 --> 00:19:27,067
I saw...

357
00:19:27,200 --> 00:19:29,700
<i>Oh my God!
Jessica! Jessica!</i>

358
00:19:30,767 --> 00:19:32,000
I saw...

359
00:19:32,800 --> 00:19:34,867
my daughter lying on the ground.

360
00:19:36,767 --> 00:19:38,667
<i> There's so much blood.</i>

361
00:19:41,033 --> 00:19:44,800
Mrs. Cruz, you may continue.

362
00:19:46,167 --> 00:19:47,733
I found out from the driver...

363
00:19:49,133 --> 00:19:52,233
that Coleen pushed Jessica,
which is why she was hit.

364
00:19:53,500 --> 00:19:55,500
It felt like I was stabbed
in the chest.

365
00:19:56,900 --> 00:19:58,467
I couldn't accept it.

366
00:20:00,133 --> 00:20:02,800
How could Coleen do that
to her own sister?

367
00:20:04,333 --> 00:20:07,267
Coleen, you're cruel.

368
00:20:08,233 --> 00:20:09,667
You're so cruel.

369
00:20:09,800 --> 00:20:11,233
Why did you kill Jessica?

370
00:20:11,367 --> 00:20:12,467
You killed Jessica!

371
00:20:12,600 --> 00:20:13,833
You killed her!

372
00:20:19,767 --> 00:20:21,867
Jessica is gone.

373
00:20:27,100 --> 00:20:28,667
On the day of the accident...

374
00:20:30,067 --> 00:20:33,867
you didn't actually see
Coleen push Jessica,

375
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:35,300
correct?

376
00:20:40,800 --> 00:20:42,700
That's right, I didn't see it.

377
00:20:42,833 --> 00:20:46,133
So, your understanding
of what happened

378
00:20:46,267 --> 00:20:49,567
is based solely
on what the driver,

379
00:20:49,700 --> 00:20:52,900
Timo Malabanan, told you,
correct?

380
00:20:54,867 --> 00:20:56,400
Yes.

381
00:20:56,533 --> 00:20:57,567
Mrs. Cruz...

382
00:20:59,233 --> 00:21:00,633
have you personally witnessed...

383
00:21:01,800 --> 00:21:03,833
Coleen threaten to kill Jessica?

384
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:09,333
No.

385
00:21:10,233 --> 00:21:15,233
So if you never witnessed Coleen
threatening Jessica...

386
00:21:16,333 --> 00:21:17,500
it's also possible that...

387
00:21:18,667 --> 00:21:20,267
what happened was really just
an accident.

388
00:21:20,400 --> 00:21:21,600
Objection, Your Honor!

389
00:21:21,733 --> 00:21:23,033
Speculative!

390
00:21:28,900 --> 00:21:31,333
What do you feel about
the victim's death?

391
00:21:31,467 --> 00:21:34,200
I'm sad because
I wasn't able to save her.

392
00:21:34,333 --> 00:21:36,733
So you feel responsible
for her death?

393
00:21:36,867 --> 00:21:39,067
I'm sad because my sister died,

394
00:21:39,200 --> 00:21:41,133
and she shouldn't have died.

395
00:21:41,267 --> 00:21:43,567
She died because you pushed her!

396
00:21:43,733 --> 00:21:45,400
You let my daughter
get run over!

397
00:21:45,533 --> 00:21:46,533
You let it happen!

398
00:21:46,667 --> 00:21:47,600
- Order!
- That's the truth!

399
00:21:47,733 --> 00:21:49,033
- Order in the court!
- Stop lying, Coleen!

400
00:21:49,167 --> 00:21:50,933
I feel sorry for my daughter.

401
00:21:51,300 --> 00:21:53,467
I hope we win
this case, Attorney.

402
00:21:53,600 --> 00:21:54,800
It's hard to say for now.

403
00:21:54,933 --> 00:21:57,200
Coleen was confused
and vulnerable.

404
00:21:57,333 --> 00:21:59,000
The court might think

405
00:21:59,133 --> 00:22:01,867
she feels guilty
about Jessica's death.

406
00:22:02,100 --> 00:22:03,833
What can we do, Attorney?

407
00:22:06,233 --> 00:22:07,567
What are you doing here?

408
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:10,967
You're here because you want me
to withdraw the case?

409
00:22:11,100 --> 00:22:12,500
Can you do that?

410
00:22:12,633 --> 00:22:14,800
How far are you willing
to go for Coleen?

411
00:22:16,467 --> 00:22:19,533
Are you willing to kiss my feet?
